  "duration": 185.289312384,
  "text": " What is organizational memory? Organizational memory is all about the collective ability to build up or accumulate, store and retrieve data and knowledge. Organizational memory has nothing to do with human or animal memory. Our ability to gain, store and retrieve data is referred to as human memory. Organizational memory extends beyond human beings It refers to organizations such as companies, charities, government departments, etc. An organization typically refers to an organized group of people The members of an organization have a specific purpose such as doing business, providing state benefits or representing groups of people who need help Corporate memory and institutional memory usually have the same meaning as organizational memory Corporate memory is only used in the world of business Some people would say that institutional memory is more about data which is of value for reuse Undocumented insights, skills, experience and knowledge acquired over time are some components of organisational memory. Employees pass on this information to new workers through training courses meetings mentoring and shadowing programs and personal contacts Organisational memory is stored in two places, the organisation's archives and the memories of individual people. The organisation's archives today are typically stored in electronic databases. Wikipedia has the following definition of the term Organizational memory is the accumulated body of data, information and knowledge created in the course of an organization's existence Humans have memories and so do organizations Organizational memory, just like human memory helps organisations not repeat the same mistakes all the time. Human memories are in one place, while those of organisations are in different places. In the business world, the organisational memory process or corporate memory process consists of three stages. They are acquisition, retention and retrieval. Thank you.",
